hip name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Walchelin</i>,  <i>Wakelin</i>, a Norman French double diminutive of the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Walho</i> or  <i>Walico</i>.  See also  Wack  ,   Walklett  , and   Walking  . The post-medieval bearers in Essex cited here may alternatively belong to   Wakeling   (1)."]},{"name":"Walkins","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Walking</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Walkin</i>, which is probably a variant of <i>Walchelin</i> with dissimilatory loss of the second <i>-l-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"]}]},{"name":"Mae","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   May  , possibly influenced by   Maeve .  It was borne by the American film actress  Mae West  (  1892–1980 ), whose prominent bust led to her name being given, by members of the RAF, to a type of inflatable life jacket used in the Second World War. This spelling is not much used, except in compounds such as <i>Ellie-Mae</i>, <i>Lily-Mae</i>, and <i>Daisy-Mae</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Mae Walking was born in 1438, in Berkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 2 d